# XPYD Prefill decode disaggregation P2P architecture via ZMQ Broker

Whimsical link: [https://whimsical.com/xpyd-p2p-via-zmq-broker-server-CWt8X7LKbQn6AB7pqQ3Zwq](https://whimsical.com/xpyd-p2p-via-zmq-broker-server-CWt8X7LKbQn6AB7pqQ3Zwq)

![][image1]

1) The request scheduler receives a request, assigns a globally unique request\_id and sends it to both prefill and decode load balancers. (i.e. 1(a) and 1(b)). For prefill it will pick max\_tokens=1 and for decode it will pass the true max\_tokens and stream the results back from the decode async request.  
2) The prefill and decode load balancers will independently pick the most appropriate replica for prefill and decode according to their own criteria (random, power of 2, round robin, etc). So the picked prefill and decode instances do not know about each otherâ€™s ip:port address.   
3) Before the prefill starts on the prefill instance it submits a message to the ZMQ broker informing that this particular instance will produce kv corresponding to the given request\_id.   
4) Before the decode starts the decode instance will submit a message to the ZMQ broker informing that this particular instance will need to consume kv corresponding the given request\_id  
5) The broker will serve both sides of the prefill and decode and will inform both sides as soon as there is a match with the ip:port address of the other party.  
6) As soon as prefill gets to know about the decode instance it will form a nccl connection with the corresponding decode party on each rank.   
7) Once the nccl channel is formed the prefill starts and pipes the kv-tensors overlapping with the computation of kv of the next layers. During this time the event loop of the decode side is kept free for processing requests whose kv is already fully transferred. For the new request, decode only starts after all of the kv layers are transferred. 

* \[Note\] This design does not incorporate any request\_id hacking which makes it more general. As a result it makes no assumptions about how proxy should be built for picking to be able to inform the prefill instance about the corresponding decode instance.   
* \[Note\] Decode instance should never compute prefill. It either does a local kv-cache look up or if there is a cache miss it should always assume there is a prefill that will come with the missing kv parts. It may just be running a bit behind so it will wait on zmq server giving the corresponding prefill connection info.
